1. STREAM PIPELINE – THE CORRECT FLOW

Every stream pipeline follows this structure:
source  →  intermediate operations  →  terminal operation

INTERMEDIATE OPS (lazy)
filter()
map()
flatMap()
sorted()
distinct()
limit()
skip()

TERMINAL OPS (trigger execution)
collect()
forEach()
reduce()
count()
min(), max()
anyMatch(), allMatch()

✅ 2. BEST PRACTICE — ORDER OF OPERATIONS

For performance and readability, always follow:
1️⃣ filter → map/flatMap → sort → collect

Reason:
Filtering early reduces data → faster
Mapping later avoids unnecessary conversion
Sorting should happen only after filtering & mapping

Example:
employees.stream()
        .filter(e -> e.getSalary() > 3000)   // reduce data first
        .map(Employee::getName)              // transform
        .sorted()                             // sort only what is needed
        .collect(Collectors.toList());

✅ 3. When to use map() vs flatMap()
✔ map() → One-to-One mapping

Input element → exactly one output element.

Example:
List<String> names = employees.stream()
        .map(Employee::getName)
        .collect(Collectors.toList());

✔ flatMap() → One-to-Many flattening

Input element → multiple elements, flattened into a single stream.

Use when you have:
List<List<T>>
List<Set<T>>
List<Objects> having list attributes

Example:
List<String> allSkills = employees.stream()
        .flatMap(e -> e.getSkills().stream())
        .collect(Collectors.toList());

